            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>727</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [70d] certainly the pure life. Will you permit [your] fervor to recede in any way? Remember me! In this way</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Will you [pl.] let [your] zeal fail? Remember me, this including!  (cf : ii, 46)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>358</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #a7 #a8 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6 #b7 #b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1949"/><citedRange>II, 46-47</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>162</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>180</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of a good being to the welfare of [one’s own] self. [71d] The way I have proclaimed to you, to the good town of Nirvāṇa, the eightfold, noble</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>337</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>754</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979b"/><citedRange>34</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (by you), however, [an] effort must be made with [your] whole self. Aside from this there is no other way to emerge from the Saṃsāra. The law (proclaimed?) by me</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [72d] || In Dharmasoma’s Udānālaṅkāra, first part of the Mārgavarga. || ||In the Nandavilāpa metre||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>93</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (and so forth) in 90 ways proclaimed to their pupils such ways differently. Themselves being on each way </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>50</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>58</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>177</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [their] own endeavours (?). There is no gift, nor even having to make a sacrifice, (nor) having to make libation. No</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>196</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (The cutting off). You yourselves deceived (?) the beings in every way, there will be no (extinction) thereby. [2d] Therefore only dust (?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>297</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... From Maskali this view had stemmed: there is no power, no energy, no</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [3d] (Without) thought they feel happiness [and] suffering. This was the view [that had come] from him. Ajita (Kesakambala)</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Ohne) Gedanken empfinden sie Glück [und] Leid.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">(Without) thought they feel bliss [and] suffering.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>199</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>325</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>53</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>724</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1967c"/><citedRange>169</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>469</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (earth, water, fire, wind), [4d] happiness and suffering and the life with them as a seventh, they will not be able to be killed. Between them the sword (passes through)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... and the bones are but white, and sage or fool, both are not distinct. [5d]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>54 n.1</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>70</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>229</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970a"/><citedRange>455</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>31</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2012b"/><citedRange>159</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">.... Whoever should ask him, exactly the same he says then, like a myna. Should one ask him [about] white, [so] he would decide white.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Wer) immer ihn fragen sollte, genau dasselbe sagte er dann, gleich wie eine Prediger-Krähe(?).</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">(Who)ever would ask him, [it is] exactly the same he said then, like a preacher-crow(?).</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>54</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>70, 304</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970a"/><citedRange>455</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (always the same(?)) he replied. [6d] By Jñāti’s son, the (Ni(r))grantha, the view was firmly taken. Who should ask him, [to him] he would replay: I am (the omniscient)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>70</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970a"/><citedRange>455</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>81</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Always my (knowledge) is (as the) knowledge of the omniscient, this he would reply. [7d] The views, that they themselves had taken,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Thus [also] other teachers without number were different in the countries, [but to their] pupils they did not proclaim the whole knowledge.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>68, 194</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [8d] ... Countless he saw sufferings; for the sake of the beings, the five births, he always had this wish:</seg></seg></choice></p>
